}\n{{Drama Desk Awards}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Drama Desk Award Musical Book}}\n[[Category:Drama Desk Awards|Musical Book]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox award\n| name        = [[Drama Desk Award]] <br> for Outstanding Book of a Musical\n| description = Outstanding Book of a Musical\n| presenter   = [[Drama Desk]]\n| location    = United States\n| holder      = [[Robert Horn (writer)|Robert Horn]] for ''[[Tootsie (musical)|Tootsie]]'' <small>(2019)</small>\n| website     = [http://www.dramadeskawards.com DramaDeskAwards.com]\n}}\nThe [[Drama Desk Award]] for '''Outstanding Book of a Musical''' is an annual award presented by [[Drama Desk]] in recognition of achievements in the theatre among Broadway, Off Broadway and Off-Off Broadway productions. For two years, in addition to the award for Outstanding Book, an award was presented to the writers of the '''Most Promising Book'''. Recipients of this honor were [[Melvin Van Peebles]] for ''[[Ain't Supposed to Die a Natural Death]]'' in 1972 and Ron House and Diz White for ''El Grande de Coco-Cola'' in 1973.\n\n\u2020 \u2013 indicates the book ''won'' the [[Tony Award for Best Book of a Musical|Tony Award]] <br>\n\u2021 \u2013 indicates the book was also ''nominated'' for the [[Tony Award for Best Book of a Musical|Tony Award]]\n\n==Winners and nominees==\n===1970s===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:98%;\"\n|- style=\"background:#bebebe;\"\n! style=\"width:10%;\"| Year\n! style=\"width:30%;\"| Writer\n! style=\"width:60%;\"| Production\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" align=\"center\"| 1970\n|- style=\"background:#B0C4DE\"\n| '''[[George Furth]]'''\n| '''''[[Company (musical)|Company]]'' \u2020'''\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" align=\"center\"| 1971\n|- style=\"background:#B0C4DE\"\n| '''[[Burt Shevelove]]'''\n| '''''[[No, No, Nanette]]'''''\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" align=\"center\"| 1972\n|- style=\"background:#B0C4DE\"\n| '''[[John Guare]] and [[Mel Shapiro]]'''\n| '''''[[Two Gentlemen of Verona (musical)|Two Gentlemen of Verona]]'' \u2020'''\n|